MOVIE RECOMMENDATION SYSTEM using Machine Learning

Content-Based Recommender System

Overview

The Content-Based Recommender System suggests movies based on the similarity of their

content, such as genres, keywords, cast, crew, and overview. It works by using natural language

processing (NLP) techniques to transform these attributes into a vector space and then

calculates similarity using cosine similarity. The system is built with Python and various

machine learning libraries, such as Pandas, Scikit-learn, and NLTK.

Coding Language and Environment

a. Programming Language: Python 3.13.0

b. Libraries/Frameworks:

1\. Pandas: For data manipulation and analysis.

2\. NumPy: For numerical operations.

3\. Ast: To convert string representations of lists into actual lists.

4\. NLTK: For text preprocessing, specifically stemming.

5\. Scikit-learn: For machine learning tasks like vectorization and calculating cosine

similarity.

6\. Streamlit: For creating an interactive web interface.

7\. Requests: For fetching external movie data using The Movie Database (TMDb)

API.

8\. Pickle: For saving and loading preprocessed data.

c. Development Environment:

1\. IDE: Visual Studio Code

2\. Operating System: Windows 11 24h2

Machine Specifications

The system was developed and tested on the following machine configuration:

• Processor: Intel Core i5 12450H

• RAM: 16 GB DDR4

• Storage: 500 GB SSD

• Operating System: Windows 11 24h2

• Python Version: Python 3.13.0

Steps Involved

• Data Preprocessing

The dataset contains movie information and movie credits (cast and crew). These

datasets are merged based on the movie title, followed by various preprocessing steps:

a. Handle Missing Data: Drop any rows with missing values.

b. Remove Duplicates: Ensure there are no duplicate entries.

c. Handle Genres, Keywords, Cast, Crew:

1\. Genres and Keywords are converted from string representations of lists into

actual lists.



<a name="br2"></a> 

2\. Cast is limited to the top 3 actors for simplicity.

3\. Crew information is used to extract the director.

A new column, tags, is created by concatenating the processed genres, keywords,

cast, crew, and overview (split into words). All of this text is then converted to

lowercase and stemmed.

• Vectorization and Similarity Calculation

Using CountVectorizer from Scikit-learn, the textual data in the tags column is

vectorized into a numerical format (word count vectors). After vectorization, Cosine

Similarity is used to calculate the similarity between movies based on the tags.

• Movie Recommendation

Given a movie, the system uses the cosine similarity scores to recommend the top 5

most similar movies. The results are displayed using an interactive web interface built

with Streamlit.

Code Explanation

• Libraries Used:

a. pandas and numpy for data manipulation.

b. nltk for natural language processing (specifically, stopwords removal).

c. TfidfVectorizer from sklearn to transform text data into numerical values based on

Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency.

d. cosine\_similarity from sklearn to compute similarity scores between movies.

e. pickle for saving and loading data to avoid repetitive computations.

• Load and Prepare Data:

a. Load Data: Reads a CSV file named movies\_data.csv into a DataFrame (df).

b. Fill Missing Values: Replaces any NaN values with an empty string to handle

missing data.

• Combine Relevant Features:

a. Create Combined Text: Concatenates several columns (genres, keywords, cast,

crew, and tags) into a single text field called combined\_features. This field

represents each movie’s unique “profile” for similarity calculations.

• Text Preprocessing:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

<a name="br3"></a> 

a. Stopwords Setup: Loads the English stopwords from NLTK to exclude common,

unimportant words.

b. Preprocess Function: Defines a function that:

1\. Splits the text into individual words.

2\. Removes any word that appears in the stopwords list.

c. Apply Preprocessing: Applies the preprocess\_text function to each entry in the

combined\_features column to clean the text data.

• TF-IDF Vectorization:

TF-IDF Transformation:

a. Initializes a TfidfVectorizer, which transforms text into numerical values based on

word frequency and importance.

b. Converts the combined\_features column into a matrix where each row represents a

movie, and each column represents a term (after stopword removal).

c. The resulting tfidf\_matrix is used for calculating similarity between movies.

• Calculate Cosine Similarity:

Cosine Similarity Matrix:

a. Calculates pairwise cosine similarity between all movies.

b. Stores results in cosine\_sim, where each element represents the similarity score

between two movies.

Movie Indices Dictionary:

a. Maps movie\_id to DataFrame indices for efficient look-up in the recommendation

function.

• Recommendation Function:

a. Function Purpose: Given a movie title, this function returns a list of similar movies.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

<a name="br4"></a> 

b. Find Movie by Title:

1\. Searches for the movie title in a case-insensitive way.

2\. If the movie is not found, it returns "Movie not found."

3\. Otherwise, it retrieves the index of the first match.

c. Get Similarity Scores:

1\. Extracts similarity scores between the target movie (idx) and all others.

2\. Sorts these scores in descending order.

d. Select Top Recommendations:

1\. Retrieves the top num\_recommendations movies, skipping the first entry (which

is the input movie itself).

2\. Returns the movie\_id, title, and overview columns of the recommended movies.

• Save Model Data Using Pickle:

Save Data:

a. Saves the DataFrame (df) and similarity matrix (cosine\_sim) to pickle files

(movie\_list.pkl and movie\_similarity.pkl).

b. This allows reloading the data without recalculating the entire matrix every time,

improving efficiency.

Artifacts

The following files are saved for future use:

• movie\_list.pkl: Contains the processed movie data.

• similarity.pkl: Contains the precomputed cosine similarity matrix.

These files are loaded in the Streamlit app to provide quick recommendations without needing

to reprocess the data.
